# Axis 19 — residual forwarding through nested handlers

The inner handler knows only `Rd`; both `Wr` operations must remain explicit
`Op`s for the outer handler. Resuming the first `Wr` re-enters the inner
handler, which consumes `Rd`, then re-enters the outer handler for the second
`Wr`. The `Return` transforms prove both handlers are reinstated and each maps
the final continuation completion exactly once.

```scalascript
effect Rd:
  def rd(): Int

effect Wr:
  def wr(value: Int): Unit

def prog(): Int =
  Wr.wr(7)
  val value = Rd.rd()
  Wr.wr(5)
  value + 7

def inner(): Int =
  handle(prog()) {
    case Rd.rd(resume) => resume(35)
    case Return(value) => value + 1
  }

val result = handle(inner()) {
  case Wr.wr(value, resume) => value + resume(())
  case Return(value) => value + 2
}

println(result)
```
